{{Hindu philosophy}}
'''AmanaskatƒÅ''' is the alert state of dynamic fullness of the self (''[[Atman (Hinduism)|atman]]''), it is the condition where there is no mind, the mindless state; it is the state when the mind dissolves and the self shines.<ref>{{cite book|title=Astadala Yogamala Vol.7|author=B.K.S.Iyengar|publisher=Allied Publishers|page=197|url= https://books.google.co.in/books?id=G6M-M1dNh3QC&pg=PA197&dq=amanaskata&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jTKQVLiCJ5LmuQSKgoLoCw&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=amanaskata&f=false }}</ref> It is the transmental state which is also called no-mindedness (''unmani'') and yogic sleep (''[[yoga-nidra]]'') as the prolonged absorption in the formless ecstasy or ''[[nirvikalpa samadhi]]''; it is the state in which the [[jivanmukta]] (liberated being) exists experiencing a sense of universality.<ref>{{cite book|title=Yoga: The Technology of Ecstasy|author=Georg Feuerstein|publisher=J.P.Tarcher|page=242|url= https://books.google.co.in/books?id=zMrtAAAAIAAJ&q=amanaskata&dq=amanaskata&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jTKQVLiCJ5LmuQSKgoLoCw&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAg }}</ref> According to the ''Laya-chintana'' of [[Antahkarana]] ('mind'), the mind is absorbed in ''Mahat (''[[Buddhi]]''), 'Individual Buddhi' is absorbed in the 'Cosmic Buddhi', 'Cosmic Buddhi' in ''[[Avyakta]]'' which is [[Brahman]]; in other words, the effect is absorbed into cause.<ref>{{cite book|title=Meditation and Mantras|author=Vishnu Devananda|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|page=122|url= https://books.google.co.in/books?id=JgnTT0eqwIoC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=laya+chintana&source=bl&ots=0uzoWCnNS5&sig=G9zqk5KVwCi0hQ2FyEBRmKmD5Ac&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3CCRVKXDNM-MuASJ2IDoBQ&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=laya%20chintana&f=false }}</ref>

