'''Warnock's dilemma''', named for its originator Bryan Warnock, is the problem of interpreting a lack of response to a posting in a [[virtual community]].{{sfn|Holiday|2012|pp=101-103}} The term originally referred to [[Electronic mailing list|mailing list discussions]], but has been applied to [[Usenet]] posts, [[blog]]s, [[Internet forum|Web forum]]s, and online content in general.{{sfn|Holiday|2012|p=101}} The dilemma arises because a lack of response does not necessarily imply that no one is interested in the topic, but could also mean for example that readers find the content to be exceptionally good (leaving nothing for commenters to add).{{sfn|Holiday|2012|p=101}}
On many internet forums, only around [[1% rule (Internet culture)|1 percent of users create new posts]], while 9 percent reply and 90 percent are [[lurker]]s that don't contribute to the discussion.<ref name="arthur">[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2006/jul/20/guardianweeklytechnologysection2 What is the 1% rule?] by Charles Arthur, ''The Guardian'', 20 July 2006</ref> When no users reply, the original poster has no way of knowing what lurkers think of their contribution.
Warnock's dilemma leads to online writers and publishers adopting more confrontational writing strategies in order to ensure that they will get a response.{{sfn|Holiday|2012|p=102}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Say Everything: How Blogging Began, What It's Becoming, and Why It Matters|page=259 |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0307451380|isbn=0307451380 |first=Scott |last=Rosenberg |year=2009 }}</ref> However, this can also lead publishers to avoid producing the kind of content that might fail to generate comments due to its high quality.{{sfn|Holiday|2012|pp=102-103}} This problem arises particularly with sites that focus on [[viral content]], such as ''[[Buzzfeed]]'' and ''[[Huffington Post]]''.{{sfn|Holiday|2012|pp=102-103}}
==Original description==
{{cquote|The problem with no response is that there are five possible interpretations:
# The post is correct, well-written information that needs no follow-up commentary. There's nothing more to say except "Yeah, what he said." # The post is complete and utter nonsense, and no one wants to waste the energy or bandwidth to even point this out. # No one read the post, for whatever reason. # No one understood the post, but won't ask for clarification, for whatever reason. # No one cares about the post, for whatever reason.|||Bryan C. Warnock|<ref>[http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.bootstrap/1127 Re: RFCs: two proposals for change] -- Original description of the dilemma</ref>}}
Since Warnock's original description of the dilemma in August 2000, the expression has become used in the [[Perl]] world.<ref>[http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl6.language/15407 Re: Warnocked?] -- Post to the Perl 6 language list explaining history and uptake of term</ref>{{Dubious|date=December 2018}}
